This table is how the ecu calculates 100% load at x rpm. This is important for proper automatic transmission shifting. Lower your BFS at the specific RPM's till your calculated load is showing 100% consistently at max TVO.

This is tied to coolant temp and only used when the coolant temp is under a certain set point. This needs to be kept close to the "High Octane Ignition Timing" map.
This is the main trimming map that the ECU uses when high-octane fuel is determined. You may add or remove "128" from any cell to enable or disable knock sensor feedback in said cell. The ECU calculates a MBT ignition advance, then this trimming map value is added/subtracted from that value. However, there are other compensations that occur as well.
This trimming map is used by the ecu when it detects high detonation. This map should ALWAYS be lower than the high octane map.

This table represents airflow through the maf sensor at a given voltage. The ecu uses this to calculate many things including timing and fueling. mTCCLV This table is how the ecu calculates 100% load at x rpm. The values shown are 100% load calculated from the base fuel schedule milliseconds. This is important for proper automatic transmission shifting. It needs to be adjusted so that the ecu sees at or near 100% when wide open throttle to correctly shift the automatic transmission.
